<ArticleLayout
  title="Shower Storage That Does Not Get in the Way"
  description="Before buying shower storage, check shower size, bottle weight, drainage, surface type, suction or adhesive suitability, razors, cleaning access, moisture and rental limits."
  category="Bathroom"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/bathroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy shower area with practical storage, warm bathroom finishes and soft natural light"
>
  <p>
    Shower storage can look like a simple purchase until the caddy slips, bottles fall, water
    pools, razors sit within reach of children, or the organiser makes the shower harder to
    clean.
  </p>
  <p>
    A shower is not the same as a dry bathroom cabinet. It has water, steam, soap residue,
    tile, glass, grout, sealant, drainage, movement space and surfaces that may not suit every
    suction, adhesive, hanging or drilled product.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying a shower caddy, shelf, basket, hook or organiser, check the shower itself
    and the products you actually use.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide explains what to check before buying shower storage for an Australian bathroom.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with what needs to stay in the shower</h2>
  <p>
    Not every bathroom product needs to live in the shower.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying storage, list what is actually used while showering.
  </p>
  <p>Common shower items include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shampoo</li>
    <li>conditioner</li>
    <li>body wash</li>
    <li>soap</li>
    <li>face cleanser</li>
    <li>shaving cream</li>
    <li>razors</li>
    <li>bath toys</li>
    <li>hair treatments</li>
    <li>exfoliating products</li>
    <li>loofahs or sponges</li>
    <li>shower brushes</li>
    <li>body scrub</li>
    <li>children's wash products</li>
    <li>spare bottles</li>
    <li>cleaning brush or squeegee</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Then remove anything that is not used regularly in the shower.
  </p>
  <p>
    Many showers become crowded because old bottles, nearly empty products, duplicates and
    occasional treatments are left in the wet zone. A larger caddy may hide the problem
    rather than solve it.
  </p>

  <h2>Sort daily products from occasional products</h2>
  <p>
    Shower storage should prioritise daily use.
  </p>
  <p>Sort products into simple groups.</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Product group</th>
        <th>Examples</th>
        <th>Storage implication</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Daily use</td>
        <td>shampoo, conditioner, body wash</td>
        <td>needs easy reach and drainage</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Weekly use</td>
        <td>treatments, scrubs, masks</td>
        <td>may not need prime shower space</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shared products</td>
        <td>family shampoo, children's wash</td>
        <td>needs reachable shared storage</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Personal products</td>
        <td>shaving items, skincare, specialty products</td>
        <td>may need separate zones</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Controlled items</td>
        <td>razors, blades, small sharp items</td>
        <td>needs extra caution</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Remove or relocate</td>
        <td>old bottles, duplicates, unused products</td>
        <td>should not drive storage purchases</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    If a product is used once a month, it may not need to sit permanently in the shower.
    Keeping fewer items in the wet zone usually makes cleaning easier.
  </p>

  <h2>Check shower size and movement space</h2>
  <p>
    A shower caddy that holds enough bottles can still be a poor choice if it crowds the
    shower.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, measure or check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shower width</li>
    <li>shower depth</li>
    <li>where people stand</li>
    <li>shower head position</li>
    <li>shower hose movement</li>
    <li>shower screen or curtain movement</li>
    <li>door swing</li>
    <li>where elbows and shoulders move</li>
    <li>whether a caddy would be bumped</li>
    <li>whether children use the shower</li>
    <li>whether a stool, bath seat or other aid is used</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not measure only the wall. Check the space as it is used.
  </p>
  <p>
    In small showers, a compact caddy or fewer products may work better than a large shelf
    system.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the shower surface</h2>
  <p>
    Shower storage depends heavily on the surface it attaches to or rests on.
  </p>
  <p>Surfaces may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>smooth tile</li>
    <li>textured tile</li>
    <li>grout lines</li>
    <li>glass</li>
    <li>acrylic</li>
    <li>fibreglass</li>
    <li>stone or stone-look surfaces</li>
    <li>painted or coated surfaces</li>
    <li>metal frames</li>
    <li>shower screens</li>
    <li>shower rails</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Before buying suction, adhesive or mounted storage, check whether the product is suitable
    for the exact surface. A product that works on smooth tile may not suit textured tile,
    grout lines, damp surfaces or some coated materials.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not assume "bathroom suitable" means suitable for every shower.
  </p>

  <h2>Be cautious with suction storage</h2>
  <p>
    Suction shower storage can be convenient, especially for renters, but it is not a
    universal solution.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying suction shelves, baskets or hooks, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>approved surface types</li>
    <li>whether the surface is smooth enough</li>
    <li>whether grout lines interrupt the suction area</li>
    <li>whether the surface gets wet constantly</li>
    <li>product weight limits</li>
    <li>bottle weight when full</li>
    <li>whether the product needs regular reattachment</li>
    <li>whether failure could break bottles or create a hazard</li>
    <li>whether children may pull on it</li>
    <li>whether the organiser will be bumped while showering</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not use suction storage for heavy, glass, sharp or fragile items unless the product
    instructions clearly support that use and the surface is suitable.
  </p>
  <p>
    Suction products should be treated as surface-dependent, not guaranteed.
  </p>

  <h2>Be cautious with adhesive shelves</h2>
  <p>
    Adhesive shower shelves can look neat, but they need careful checking.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying adhesive storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>product instructions</li>
    <li>approved surface types</li>
    <li>whether it is designed for wet areas</li>
    <li>weight limits</li>
    <li>required curing or waiting time</li>
    <li>whether the surface must be cleaned or dried first</li>
    <li>whether the surface is textured, dusty, coated or uneven</li>
    <li>whether removal may leave marks or residue</li>
    <li>whether the product is suitable for renters</li>
    <li>whether failure could cause breakage or injury</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Adhesive products may not suit every shower surface or every rental situation.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid relying on adhesive storage for heavy bottles, glass containers, razors or items
    that would create problems if the shelf failed.
  </p>

  <h2>Be cautious with hanging caddies</h2>
  <p>
    Hanging caddies can work over shower heads, shower screens or rails, but they are not
    suitable for every setup.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a hanging caddy, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shower head shape</li>
    <li>shower arm strength and position</li>
    <li>hose movement</li>
    <li>whether the caddy will slide</li>
    <li>whether it blocks water flow</li>
    <li>whether bottles will sit level</li>
    <li>whether it scratches or marks surfaces</li>
    <li>whether it interferes with the shower screen</li>
    <li>whether it can be removed for cleaning</li>
    <li>whether the manufacturer says it suits your shower type</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not assume a shower head, rail or screen is suitable for hanging storage. Follow
    product instructions and avoid loading the caddy beyond guidance.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the caddy swings, slips or blocks normal shower use, it is not a good fit.
  </p>

  <h2>Think carefully before drilling</h2>
  <p>
    Some shower shelves and baskets require drilling into tiles, walls or surrounding
    surfaces. This needs caution.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying drilled shower storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether drilling is allowed</li>
    <li>whether the surface is tile, stone, glass or another material</li>
    <li>whether waterproofing could be affected</li>
    <li>product installation instructions</li>
    <li>whether qualified installation is needed</li>
    <li>whether you rent or live in a body corporate property</li>
    <li>whether approval is required</li>
    <li>whether the location avoids plumbing or other services</li>
    <li>whether the shelf is necessary compared with non-fixed options</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not casually drill into bathroom or shower surfaces. If a product requires drilling
    and you are unsure about the surface, waterproofing, approval or installation, seek
    qualified advice.
  </p>

  <h2>Check bottle height, width and weight</h2>
  <p>
    Shower products vary more than people expect.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a caddy or shelf, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>tallest bottle height</li>
    <li>widest bottle width</li>
    <li>pump bottle height</li>
    <li>bottle weight when full</li>
    <li>whether bottles need to stand upright</li>
    <li>whether caps leak if bottles lie down</li>
    <li>whether pump bottles need headroom</li>
    <li>whether family-size bottles fit</li>
    <li>whether children's products fit</li>
    <li>whether the shelf has enough depth</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A caddy may fit six small bottles but not three large pump bottles. A shelf may fit the
    shower wall but not the products actually used.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure the bottles before buying storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Check drainage and water pooling</h2>
  <p>
    Shower storage must let water drain.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a caddy, shelf or basket, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether the base drains properly</li>
    <li>whether bottles sit in pooled water</li>
    <li>whether soap can dry</li>
    <li>whether the shelf catches residue</li>
    <li>whether water drips onto other items</li>
    <li>whether the organiser can be removed and cleaned</li>
    <li>whether corners are mould-prone</li>
    <li>whether the material suits wet conditions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Products that trap water can create cleaning issues. Solid trays may look tidy, but they
    may not suit wet zones unless they drain and clean easily.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing items in a way that leaves them sitting in water.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep razors and blades controlled</h2>
  <p>
    Razors are common in showers, but they need deliberate storage.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying shower hooks, cups or shelves for razors, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether children use the bathroom</li>
    <li>whether pets can access the area</li>
    <li>whether blades are exposed</li>
    <li>whether the razor drains and dries</li>
    <li>whether it can fall</li>
    <li>whether it sits near soap or shampoo bottles</li>
    <li>whether spare blades are stored elsewhere</li>
    <li>whether the holder is stable</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid loose razors on shower floors, bath edges or crowded shelves. Avoid storing spare
    blades in the shower.
  </p>
  <p>
    If children use the bathroom, choose storage with extra caution and keep sharp items
    controlled.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid crowding the shower floor</h2>
  <p>
    The shower floor should not become the default storage area.
  </p>
  <p>Avoid leaving these on the shower floor where they can clutter the space, collect residue or be kicked around:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shampoo bottles</li>
    <li>body wash</li>
    <li>soap containers</li>
    <li>razors</li>
    <li>bath toys</li>
    <li>foot files</li>
    <li>cleaning brushes</li>
    <li>loose caps</li>
    <li>spare bottles</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If products are already sitting on the floor, the first step is sorting and reducing, not
    automatically buying the largest caddy available.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan for children's bath and shower items</h2>
  <p>
    Children's bath products and toys can overwhelm a shower or shower-over-bath area.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage for children's items, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>how many toys are actually used</li>
    <li>whether toys drain and dry</li>
    <li>whether the organiser is reachable</li>
    <li>whether small items could create problems</li>
    <li>whether products need to be kept away from children</li>
    <li>whether the storage can be cleaned easily</li>
    <li>whether the area is shared by adults</li>
    <li>whether toys should be rotated rather than stored all at once</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid storing damp toys in closed containers where they cannot dry. Also avoid keeping too
    many items in the shower simply because a large basket exists.
  </p>

  <h2>Check cleaning access</h2>
  <p>
    Shower storage should not make cleaning harder.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a shelf or caddy, check whether it will:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>block cleaning around grout lines</li>
    <li>make glass harder to wipe</li>
    <li>trap soap residue</li>
    <li>hide mould-prone corners</li>
    <li>make the shower screen harder to move</li>
    <li>stop the shower head or hose moving properly</li>
    <li>need frequent removal to clean behind it</li>
    <li>collect hair or product residue</li>
    <li>make bottles harder to lift and wipe</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A storage product that saves space but creates grime is not a good long-term solution.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choose storage that can be removed, wiped, rinsed or cleaned without too much effort.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider shared showers</h2>
  <p>
    Shared bathrooms need shower storage that works for several people.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, check whether the shower needs:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>one shared product zone</li>
    <li>separate products by person</li>
    <li>children's products separated from adult products</li>
    <li>shaving items kept controlled</li>
    <li>space for different bottle heights</li>
    <li>a way to avoid duplicate products</li>
    <li>easy cleaning access</li>
    <li>clear limits on how many products stay in the shower</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A shared shower can quickly become crowded if every person keeps every product in the wet
    zone.
  </p>
  <p>
    It may be better to keep only shared daily products in the shower and store occasional or
    personal items elsewhere.
  </p>

  <h2>Be careful with glass and heavy containers</h2>
  <p>
    Glass bottles, heavy pump bottles and large containers need extra thought in a shower.
  </p>
  <p>Before storing them on a shelf or caddy, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>bottle weight when full</li>
    <li>whether the shelf or basket is rated for the load</li>
    <li>whether the bottle could fall</li>
    <li>whether the surface below is tile, bath, glass or another hard surface</li>
    <li>whether children use the shower</li>
    <li>whether the bottle becomes slippery</li>
    <li>whether a lighter or smaller container would be more practical</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid placing heavy or breakable items on questionable suction, adhesive or crowded
    storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about renters and body corporate rules</h2>
  <p>
    If you rent or live in a townhouse, unit or body corporate property, check the rules
    before buying shower storage that attaches to surfaces.
  </p>
  <p>You may need approval before:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>drilling into tiles</li>
    <li>installing fixed shelves</li>
    <li>attaching products to shower screens</li>
    <li>changing shower fittings</li>
    <li>adding wall-mounted baskets</li>
    <li>using products that may mark surfaces</li>
    <li>altering waterproofed areas</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Renter-friendly shower storage usually means non-fixed caddies, suitable freestanding or
    hanging options, or removable products only where the surface and instructions support
    them.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not assume a product is renter-friendly because it is removable. Check surface
    suitability and removal risk.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide between caddies, shelves, hooks and baskets</h2>
  <p>
    Different shower storage types solve different problems.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Storage type</th>
        <th>Works well for</th>
        <th>Check before buying</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Hanging caddies</td>
        <td>selected showers with suitable hanging points</td>
        <td>shower head, rail, screen, load, slipping</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Suction shelves</td>
        <td>light products on suitable smooth surfaces</td>
        <td>surface type, weight, wet-area performance</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Adhesive shelves</td>
        <td>selected wet-area surfaces where suitable</td>
        <td>instructions, load, removal risk, surface</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Drilled shelves</td>
        <td>permanent storage where appropriate</td>
        <td>surface, waterproofing, approval, installation</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Corner shelves</td>
        <td>unused corner space</td>
        <td>drainage, reach, cleaning, bottle height</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shower baskets</td>
        <td>bottles and soap where drainage works</td>
        <td>rust, water pooling, cleaning</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Hooks</td>
        <td>razors, loofahs, selected light items</td>
        <td>load, child access, surface suitability</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Portable caddies</td>
        <td>shared or rental bathrooms</td>
        <td>drainage, storage location, daily use</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The right choice depends on the shower, not just the product.
  </p>

  <h2>Common shower storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>Before buying, avoid these mistakes:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying a caddy before reducing old bottles</li>
    <li>relying on suction without checking the surface</li>
    <li>using adhesive storage in wet areas without checking instructions</li>
    <li>storing too many products in the shower</li>
    <li>choosing shelves that do not fit pump bottles</li>
    <li>ignoring bottle weight when full</li>
    <li>placing razors within easy child access</li>
    <li>blocking shower movement</li>
    <li>hanging storage from unsuitable shower heads or screens</li>
    <li>drilling without checking approval and surface suitability</li>
    <li>choosing solid trays that trap water</li>
    <li>storing glass bottles on questionable shelves</li>
    <li>making the shower harder to clean</li>
    <li>leaving bath toys damp in closed storage</li>
    <li>assuming all tile or glass surfaces behave the same</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Shower storage should reduce clutter without creating new cleaning, access or surface
    problems.
  </p>

  <h2>A simple shower storage checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying shower caddies or shelves, write down:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shower width and depth</li>
    <li>shower head position</li>
    <li>shower hose movement</li>
    <li>shower screen or curtain movement</li>
    <li>wall, tile or glass surface type</li>
    <li>whether the surface is smooth or textured</li>
    <li>how many products are used daily</li>
    <li>bottle height, width and weight</li>
    <li>whether pump bottles need headroom</li>
    <li>whether products need drainage</li>
    <li>whether razors or blades need controlled storage</li>
    <li>whether children use the shower</li>
    <li>whether items are heavy, glass or fragile</li>
    <li>whether the organiser will block movement</li>
    <li>whether it can be removed and cleaned</li>
    <li>moisture, mould or cleaning concerns</li>
    <li>rental or body corporate restrictions</li>
    <li>whether drilling, suction or adhesive products are suitable</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Take these notes before buying. Shower storage needs to fit the wet area, not just the
    product list.
  </p>

  <h2>Our take</h2>
  <p>
    Shower storage should start with fewer products and better surface checks.
  </p>
  <p>
    Remove old bottles first. Keep only daily-use items in the shower where possible. Measure
    the shower, check bottle sizes and think carefully about drainage, cleaning, razors,
    children and wet surfaces before buying a caddy or shelf.
  </p>
  <p>
    Be cautious with suction, adhesive and drilled storage. Check product instructions,
    surface suitability and load guidance rather than assuming a shower organiser will work
    on every tile, glass or wall surface.
  </p>
  <p>
    For many households, useful shower storage is modest: enough space for daily products,
    proper drainage, easy cleaning and controlled access to sharp items.
  </p>
  <p>
    If a caddy slips, traps water, crowds the shower or relies on a surface that may not suit
    it, it is not solving the real storage problem.
  </p>

